# Supabase safety rules

## DDL (schema changes)
- ✅ Use `mcp__supabase__apply_migration` (named, versioned, replayable)
- ❌ Never `mcp__supabase__execute_sql` for DDL — it bypasses migration history
- ✅ After every DDL: run `mcp__supabase__get_advisors` (security + performance) and resolve WARN/ERROR
- ✅ Also drop the same SQL into `supabase/migrations/<timestamp>_<name>.sql` (going forward we version migrations in git)

## Destructive ops (require explicit human "go")
- DROP TABLE
- DROP COLUMN
- ALTER TYPE (enum changes that affect existing data)
- Disabling RLS
- DELETE without WHERE
- TRUNCATE
- Removing a SECURITY DEFINER function

## RLS
- Every new table: `alter table X enable row level security;`
- Helper functions on `profiles` (is_admin, is_staff, is_banned, current_user_role): `SECURITY INVOKER`
- Functions that maintain counters / triggers: `SECURITY INVOKER` + `SET search_path = public`
- Functions exposed to anon/auth via RPC: `SECURITY DEFINER` only when truly needed; document why

## Risky DB workflow (use Supabase branches)
Staging DB == production DB. For migrations that could break data:
1. `mcp__supabase__create_branch` (cost ~$0.013/hr, confirm cost first)
2. Apply migration to branch
3. Test
4. If good: apply same migration to prod via `apply_migration`. If bad: drop branch.

## Secrets
- ❌ `SUPABASE_SERVICE_ROLE_KEY` MUST NOT appear in any `src/**` file
- ✅ Only in Edge Function env (`Deno.env.get(...)`)
- ❌ Never `console.log` a JWT or session access_token

## Edge Functions
- Default to dry-run for destructive ops (see `storage-cleanup` example)
- `verify_jwt: true` unless explicitly public (sitemap, etc.)
- Internal admin checks: query `profiles` for `role` after `auth.getUser()`
